'''Dan Meredith''', also known as '''Dan Blah''', is a [[Internet freedom]]{{disambiguation needed|date=August 2017}} supporter,<ref>{{cite news|title=BBG Leadership In Brussels For Internet Freedom Discussions|url=http://www.bbg.gov/blog/2013/05/31/bbg-leadership-in-brussels-for-internet-freedom-discussions/|accessdate=May 31, 2013|agency=Broadcasting Board of Governors|publisher=Broadcasting Board of Governors}}</ref> journalist,<ref name="AJESIM">{{cite news|title=SIM deadline to silence Nigeria?|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/insidestory/2011/09/201192983639583908.html|accessdate=29 Sep 2011|agency=Al Jazeera|publisher=Al Jazeera}}</ref> technologist,<ref name="GlanzMarkoff">{{cite news|author=[[James Glanz]] and [[John Markoff]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/12/world/12internet.html?pagewanted=all|title=U.S. Underwrites Internet Detour Around Censors|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 12, 2011|accessdate= August 8, 2011}}</ref> and media activist.<ref name="IMCfest">{{cite news|last1=Gillespie|first1=Joel|title=Dan Blah opens up about IMC Fest|url=http://www.smilepolitely.com/music/dan_blah_opens_up_about_imc_fest/|accessdate=April 15, 2009|agency=Smile Politely|publisher=Smile Politely}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Judkis|first1=Maura|title=In D.C., private ‘bucket list’ dreams become public art|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/in-dc-private-bucket-list-dreams-become-public-art/2012/05/09/gIQAJW2IEU_story_1.html|accessdate=May 10, 2012|publisher=The Washington Post}}</ref> He is currently the founding Director of the [[Open Technology Fund]], a [[U.S. Government]] funded program created in 2012 at [[Radio Free Asia]] to support global [[Internet freedom]]{{disambiguation needed|date=August 2017}}, [[privacy-enhancing technologies]], and [[Internet censorship circumvention]] technologies.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harris|first1=Shane|last2=Hudson|first2=John|title=Not Even the NSA Can Crack the State Dept's Favorite Anonymous Network|url=http://thecable.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2013/10/04/not_even_the_nsa_can_crack_the_state_departments_online_anonymity_tool|accessdate=Oct 4, 2013|issue=The Cable|publisher=Foreign Policy Magazine}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Open Technology Fund Team |url=https://www.opentechfund.org/about/team |website=Open Technology Fund |accessdate=9 August 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150429220922/https://www.opentechfund.org/about/team |archivedate=29 April 2015 |df= }}</ref> Meredith joined [[Al Jazeera Media Network|Al Jazeera's]] Transparency Unit in 2011,<ref name=ajtu>{{cite web|title=About the Transparency Unit|url=http://transparency.aljazeera.net/en/aboutus/|website=Al Jazeera Transparency Unit|publisher=Al Jazeera Network|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref> led by [[Clayton Swisher]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Clayton Swisher|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/profile/clayton-swisher.html|website=AlJazeera.com|publisher=Al Jazeera Media Network|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref> where he increased communication security between investigative field journalists and their sources.<ref name="AJESIM" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Dan Meredith a.k.a. Dan Blah's Resume / C.V. |url=http://danblah.com/resume-cv |website=Dan Blah dot com |accessdate=9 August 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830041958/https://danblah.com/resume-cv |archivedate=30 August 2014 |df= }}</ref> He was an early part of the [[Open Technology Institute]] in 2009, led by [[Sascha Meinrath]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Dan Meredith: All Related Content |url=http://newamerica.org/people/archives/248 |website=New America Foundation |publisher=New America Foundation |accessdate=9 August 2014 }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> While at OTI, Meredith was involved with: The "[[Commotion Wireless|Internet in a Suitcase]]" project, a [[U.S. Department of State]] funded effort to create ''ad hoc'' [[mesh wireless]] technologies;<ref name="GlanzMarkoff"/> collaborated with [[Philadelphia]] community organizers to secure $11.8 million USD from the federal [[National Telecommunications and Information Administration#Broadband USA|Broadband Technology Opportunities Program]];<ref>{{cite web|title=The Open Technology Initiative Helps Bring $11.8 Million for Broadband Adoption in Philadelphia |url=http://oti.newamerica.net/pressroom/2010/the_open_technology_initiative_helps_bring_118_million_for_broadband_adoption_in_phil |archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20110912160841/http://oti.newamerica.net/pressroom/2010/the_open_technology_initiative_helps_bring_118_million_for_broadband_adoption_in_phil |dead-url=yes |archive-date=12 September 2011 |website=Newamerica.net |publisher=New America Foundation |accessdate=9 August 2014 }}</ref> and, worked on [[Network Neutrality]] court cases [[Hart v. Comcast]] and [[Comcast Corp. v. FCC]] with Robb Topolski,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Calabrese |first1=Michael |last2=Meinrath |first2=Sascha |last3=Lennett |first3=Benjamin |last4=Meredith |first4=Dan |last5=Topolski |first5=Robb |title=Reply Comments on Preserving Open Internet and Broadband Industry Practices |url=http://oti.newamerica.net/publications/resources/2010/reply_comments_on_preserving_open_internet_and_broadband_industry_practi |website=Newamerica.net |publisher=New America Foundation |accessdate=9 August 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110617181542/http://oti.newamerica.net/publications/resources/2010/reply_comments_on_preserving_open_internet_and_broadband_industry_practi |archivedate=17 June 2011 |df= }}</ref> who discovered Comcast blocking [[Bittorrent]] traffic in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roth|first1=Daniel|title=The Dark Lord of Broadband Tries to Fix Comcast's Image|url=http://archive.wired.com/techbiz/people/magazine/17-02/mf_brianroberts?currentPage=all|accessdate=2009-01-19|agency=Wired.com|publisher=Condé Nast}}</ref> Meredith was a co-founder and Senior [[Network Engineer]] of the [[Champaign-Urbana Community Wireless Network|CUWiN Foundation]], a non-profit launched in 2000 that aimed to develop "decentralized, community-owned networks that foster democratic cultures and local content".<ref>{{cite web|title=CUWiN Core Staff |url=http://www.cuwin.net/about/staff |website=CUWiN on the Internet Archive |accessdate=Apr 20, 2007 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070420205523/http://www.cuwin.net/about/staff |archivedate=April 20, 2007 }}</ref> He was an active [[Indymedia]] volunteer throughout the mid 2000s at the [[Independent Media Center|Champaign-Urbana Independent Media Center (UCIMC)]] and its [[low power FM]] [[radio station]], [[WRFU-LP|Radio Free Urbana WRFU-LP]].<ref name="IMCfest"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dixon |first1=Vince |title=Urbana media center festival aims to raise funds |url=http://www.dailyillini.com/features/article_b658a871-05e0-5ad1-a918-016e3181ea13.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140925101935/http://www.dailyillini.com/features/article_b658a871-05e0-5ad1-a918-016e3181ea13.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=September 25, 2014 |accessdate=November 9, 2007 |agency=The Daily Illini |publisher=Illini Media }}</ref> Meredith joined the [[Linux Foundation|Linux Foundation's]] [[Core Infrastructure Initiative]] as an inaugural appointee to its Advisory Board in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Core Infrastructure Initiative: Who's on the Advisory Board? |url=http://www.linuxfoundation.org/programs/core-infrastructure-initiative/faq#faq5 |website=Linux Foundation |accessdate=9 August 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708094611/http://www.linuxfoundation.org/programs/core-infrastructure-initiative/faq |archivedate=8 July 2014 |df= }}</ref>

